blockStates.name: Satellite Orbits
blockStates.userText:
This page shows the visual code for 
solving the two-body problem in three
dimensions: 

u₁' = Gm₂(x₂-x₁)/r³
x₁' = u₁
v₁' = Gm₂(y₂-y₁)/r³
y₁' = v₁
w₁' = Gm₂(z₂-z₁)/r³
z₁' = w₁
u₂' = Gm₁(x₁-x₂)/r³
x₂' = u₂
v₂' = Gm₁(y₁-y₂)/r³
y₂' = v₂
w₂' = Gm₁(z₁-z₂)/r³
z₂' = w₂

where t is time, m₁ and m₂ are the masses,
(x₁,y₁,z₁) are the coordinates of the first 
body, (x₂, y₂, z₂) are the coordinates of the 
second body, r is the distance between 
them, and G is the gravitational constant 
(6.674×10⁻¹¹ m³⋅kg⁻¹⋅s⁻²). 

To check if our simulation is accurate 
enough, we can also calculate and 
plot the mean velocities of the two bodies:

uₘ=(m₁u₁+m₂u₂)/(m₁+m₂)
vₘ=(m₁v₁+m₂v₂)/(m₁+m₂)
wₘ=(m₁w₁+m₂w₂)/(m₁+m₂)

as well as the total energy:

E=½m₁(u₁²+v₁²+w₁²)+½m₂(u₂²+v₂²+w₂²)
  -Gm₁m₂/r

Due to the law of momentum and energy 
conservation for an isolated system, the 
mean velocities and the total energy 
should stay approximately constant.
